ear":1792,"city":"Philadelphia","state":"Pennsylvania"},"death":{"year":1864,"city":"Philadelphia","state":"Pennsylvania"},"parents":{"father_id":"H00913","mother_id":"X00619"},"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"X00621","children_ids":["HD1935_jeb","HD1936_mary","HD1937_sarah","HD1938","HD1939_julia","HD1940","HD1941","HD1942","HD1943","HD1944"],"marriage_number":1,"date_year":1817}],"tags":["dna_confirmed_2018","unacknowledged_by_burr","abolitionist","underground_railroad"],"sources":[{"short":"Wikipedia","note":"Aaron Burr — children section"}],"cross_connections":[{"type":"double_descent","notes":"The moral inversion across one generation is among the most compelling threads in the tree.","related_id":"HD1915","display_label":"John Pierre Burr was the unacknowledged son of Aaron Burr.","link_text":"John Pierre Burr"},{"type":"double_descent","notes":"The moral inversion across one generation is among the most compelling threads in the tree.","related_id":"H00913","display_label":"John Pierre Burr was the unacknowledged son of Aaron Burr.","link_text":"Aaron Burr Jr."}],"gender":"male","notable":{"is_notable":true,"notable_category":[],"notable_blurb":"Abolitionist reformer"},"narrative_blocks":[{"header":"Underground Railroad — his Philadelphia barbershop was a station","detail":"His abolitionist activity extended beyond the Underground Railroad: he was an agent for William Lloyd Garrison's The Liberator, chairman of the American Moral Reform Society, and active in the National Black Convention movement. He was also a painter — he copied a portrait of Theodosia Burr Alston (his unacknowledged half-sister) for his unacknowledged half-sister Louisa, a detail that makes the family's fractured inheritance almost unbearably vivid. (Aaron Burr Association records; FindAGrave)","body":"John Pierre Burr operated a barbershop at Fifth and Locust Streets in Philadelphia where, by day, he cut white men's hair, and by night he and his wife Hetty hid self-liberating enslaved people in their attic, a cellar cave, and a deep backyard hole.","number":1},{"header":"Aaron Burr's unacknowledged son","detail":"He was born in 1792, the grandson of Princeton president Aaron Burr Sr. and great-grandson of Princeton president Jonathan Edwards — yet barred by race from attending Princeton. His father Aaron Burr Jr. had attempted to abolish slavery in New York in 1785 — a bill that failed by one vote. John Pierre Burr lived the principle his father failed to legislate: he ran an active Underground Railroad station for decades. The moral arithmetic of the Hooker-Edwards-Burr line runs from Jonathan Edwards's theology to Aaron Burr Jr.'s failed abolition bill to John Pierre Burr's barbershop safe house — and then, in 2018, to a headstone finally claiming his name. (Aaron Burr Association; FindAGrave; DNA confirmation records)","body":"John Pierre Burr was the son of Aaron Burr Jr. and Mary Emmons. DNA evidence accepted by the Aaron Burr Association in 2018 confirmed his ancestry, after which the Association installed a headstone at his previously unmarked grave declaring his lineage.","number":2},{"header":"His wife Hetty's father served at Valley Forge","detail":"The coincidence is documentary: John Emery, the future father-in-law of Aaron Burr's unacknowledged son, was at Valley Forge when Burr was there. They were on the same side of the same war. Twenty years later, their children would marry. This detail, preserved in the muster rolls, illuminates how the Revolutionary War mixed people across racial lines in shared suffering — and how those connections were simultaneously honored and dishonored in the generation that followed. (Pennsylvania Fifth Regiment muster rolls; Aaron Burr Association records)","body":"Hetty Emery Burr's father John Emery served four times in the muster rolls of Pennsylvania's Fifth Regiment at Valley Forge — the same winter Aaron Burr Jr. was wintering there as an officer.","number":3}],"number_of_marriages":1,"bio":{"display_name":"John Pierre Burr","first_name":"John","last_name":"Burr","middle_name":"Pierre","married_names":[]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST023"},{"institution_id":"INST026"}],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"slug":"john-burr-1792"},"X00621":{"id":"X00621","has_descendants_documented":false,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{"year":1796,"city":"Philadelphia","state":"Pennsylvania"},"death":{"year":1862,"month":3,"day":19,"city":"Philadelphia","state":"Pennsylvania"},"tags":["abolitionist","underground_railroad","womens_rights"],"sources":[{"short":"Wikipedia","note":"Aaron Burr; WikiTree"}],"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"HD1915","children_ids":["HD1935_jeb","HD1936_mary","HD1937_sarah","HD1938","HD1939_julia","HD1940","HD1941","HD1942","HD1943","HD1944"],"marriage_number":1,"date_year":1817}],"gender":"female","notable":{"is_notable":true,"notable_category":[],"notable_blurb":"Abolitionist reformer"},"number_of_marriages":1,"parents":{},"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Hester Elizabeth Emery Burr","nickname":"Hetty","first_name":"Hester","last_name":"Burr","married_names":["Burr"],"middle_name":"Elizabeth","maiden_name":"Emery"},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST026"}],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"social_reform","header":"She helped open a refuge for Black women","body":"A member of the Philadelphia Female Anti-Slavery Society, Hester Burr co-founded the Moral Reform Retreat — the city’s first shelter for African American women. She worked the Women’s Anti-Slavery Conventions of 1838 and 1839 and the Colored Female Free Produce Society."},{"number":2,"category":"family","header":"Her home was a station on the railroad","body":"With her husband John Pierre Burr she raised ten children and ran an Underground Railroad station from their house at Fifth and Locust Streets. Her father had mustered with Pennsylvania’s Fifth Regiment through the Revolution, four times at Valley Forge."}],"slug":"hester-emery-1796"}},"burialCemetery":null,"institutionsById":{},"crossConnections":[]}